# aipc_agent_network — SELinux policy for aipc-agent-orchestrator.service
#
# A plain systemd unit (Type=simple, no SELinuxContext= override) runs as
# init_t, which has no `name_connect` to unreserved_port_t by default —
# hardware-verified 2026-07-05: the supervisor's outbound call to the
# LiteLLM gateway (127.0.0.1:4000) hung until this was granted, confirmed
# via `ausearch -m avc` showing `denied { name_connect } ... dest=4000
# tcontext=system_u:object_r:unreserved_port_t:s0`. Same class of gap as
# other custom systemd units on this image (see llm-lemonade's
# configure-lemonade.sh for the sibling execute/map version of this).
#
# Generated from the real denial via:
#   sudo ausearch -m avc -ts recent --raw | grep "dest=4000" | audit2allow -M aipc_agent_network
# then hand-trimmed: the raw audit2allow output also bundled an unrelated
# port-443 rule (langchain_litellm's bundled litellm SDK opportunistically
# fetching a remote model-cost-map from GitHub on init, already gracefully
# handled with a local fallback per its own warning log — not something to
# grant broader network access for) and var_lib_t execute/map rules that
# were an artifact of testing at the live-hotfix path (/var/lib/aipc-agent
# instead of the read-only /usr) — the real /usr/lib/aipc-agent path gets
# lib_t automatically, which already has execute/map without a custom rule.
#
# unreserved_port_t is broad (all of 1024-65535), not just port 4000 —
# SELinux has no port-specific type for 4000 without first reclassifying
# it via `semanage port`, which would be a heavier, more invasive change
# for one internal gateway port. This is the granularity actually
# available; revisit if it ever needs tightening.
module aipc_agent_network 1.0;

require {
	type init_t;
	type unreserved_port_t;
	class tcp_socket name_connect;
}

#============= init_t ==============
allow init_t unreserved_port_t:tcp_socket name_connect;
